obstructions per hour,

01:53.614 --> 01:55.449
but not enough
to warrant a CPAP.

01:55.549 --> 01:57.852
At least from the point of view
of your insurance company.

01:58.119 --> 01:59.754
So it's up to you
if you want one,

01:59.854 --> 02:01.889
but it probably
won't be covered.

02:03.457 --> 02:04.992
So he has sleep apnea?

02:05.093 --> 02:05.927
Yes.

02:06.027 --> 02:06.994
But it's mild.

02:07.095 --> 02:09.831
I would recommend
he sleep with a mouth guard.

02:10.230 --> 02:11.498
You can get one
over the counter,

02:11.598 --> 02:13.233
or we can fit you for one.

02:13.333 --> 02:15.268
It will position his jaw
in such a way

02:15.368 --> 02:17.605
that his breathing
will be unobstructed.

02:18.005 --> 02:19.807
Should also
take care of your snoring.

02:19.907 --> 02:22.009
But I might add
that diet and exercise

02:22.110 --> 02:23.644
could help with that as well.

02:23.911 --> 02:25.613
What about his sleep talking?

02:27.414 --> 02:28.182
Sleep talking?

02:28.348 --> 02:29.684
Yeah, that's why
we did this whole study

02:29.784 --> 02:31.219
to begin with, remember?

02:33.154 --> 02:35.555
Study shows
no evidence of somniloquy.

02:35.656 --> 02:37.658
And you recorded him
the entire time?

02:38.726 --> 02:40.393
Was the microphone working?

02:40.494 --> 02:41.328
Yes.

02:41.763 --> 02:42.462
But how do you know?

02:42.764 --> 02:44.665
Because the technician
would have been alerted

02:44.766 --> 02:46.734
had it stopped
at any point during the study.

02:46.834 --> 02:47.769
Where was
the microphone placed?

02:47.935 --> 02:49.670
- Was it a camera?
- It was taped near his throat,

02:49.771 --> 02:51.005
along with the other electrodes

02:51.105 --> 02:53.273
that were recording
his body functions.

02:53.373 --> 02:55.943
- It's un-fucking-believable.
- Honey, now look...

02:56.043 --> 02:57.879
Did he actually sleep
through the entire study?

02:57.979 --> 02:58.746
I mean, you said so yourself,

02:59.147 --> 03:00.915
you couldn't sleep with
all those wires attached to you.

03:01.015 --> 03:03.651
The report says
that he had five hours of sleep.

03:05.086 --> 03:06.586
He talks in his sleep
every night,

03:06.687 --> 03:08.588
and every night
it's the same conversation.

03:09.157 --> 03:11.291
Okay, I'm sorry.
Alex, would you not raise...

03:11.391 --> 03:12.660
He's talking to another woman.

03:12.760 --> 03:13.728
How do you know
it's another woman?

03:13.828 --> 03:15.930
Because he says both sides
of the conversation,

03:16.030 --> 03:18.298
and it's one
we've never had before.

03:18.666 --> 03:20.735
- Okay, this is kinda crazy.
- Stop saying that.

03:21.836 --> 03:22.703
Stop it.

03:24.471 --> 03:25.472
I'm not crazy.

03:25.572 --> 03:26.540
Honey, I didn't
say you were crazy.

03:26.641 --> 03:28.575
I said this, this is crazy.

03:29.644 --> 03:31.344
Have you tried recording it?

03:31.679 --> 03:32.579
Yes.

03:33.614 --> 03:35.315
And it never sounds the same.

03:35.415 --> 03:36.583
Because of that
stupid sound machine

03:36.684 --> 03:37.985
that you bought me.

03:38.085 --> 03:39.720
We got it to help
Alex sleep at night.

03:39.821 --> 03:41.388
Yeah, some help that was.

03:42.790 --> 03:44.692
And how are you sleeping,
then, Alex?

03:46.027 --> 03:46.894
